{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d1ac043-89df-4741-b4d4-65818efbb6d0","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK required. Inside your container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace (Ctrl+C to stop)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- Use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64` if you're on ARM.\n- The output `.nettrace` file can be analyzed with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert with `dotnet-trace convert`).\n- To copy the trace out: `docker cp <container>:/tmp/trace.nettrace .`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"49bd9a11-c17b-4f46-b603-a4828a5648e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required)\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version directly from Microsoft's distribution channel\n3. For .NET 8 on Linux, you'd use the `dotnet-trace` tool\n\n\n4. I should provide the specific steps for getting the standalone tool into the container and using it to capture the trace.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"9435:170FAA:1949517:1C90EE9:69E81E53"},"id":"d3ff7b4f-ea18-46f6-95c8-28da8b4acd07","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:24.742Z","parentId":"3522d326-059d-494c-833a-c1f9d29ac52a"}
